com.google.flightmap.common.geo
Class MercatorProjection

java.lang.Object
  com.google.flightmap.common.geo.MercatorProjection

public class MercatorProjection
extends Object

Converts between latitude,longitude and pixels in Mercator space. Mercator pixel space is a square with the size determined by the zoom level. Zoom 0 is the more coarse, and each integer increment of the zoom level doubles the length of a side of the square. Fractional zoom levels are supported.

The center of the square is always at latitude 0, longitude 0.

See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mercator_projection for the math.

toPoint

public static void toPoint(double zoom,
                           LatLng location,
                           int[] point,
                           int offset)
Converts location to a point in Mercator pixel space.

Parameters:
zoom - zoom level.
location - location to convert to a point.
point - an array with at least 2 elements. On return point[offset] = x, point[offset + 1] = y.
offset - starting index from which results will be written in point

toPoint

Converts location to a point in Mercator pixel space.

Same as calling toPoint(double, LatLng, int[], int) with offset equal to 0.

fromPoint

public static LatLng fromPoint(double zoom,
                               int[] point)
Returns a LatLng corresponding to point (in Mercator pixel space).

Parameters:
zoom - zoom level. See toPoint(double, com.google.flightmap.common.data.LatLng, int[], int) for details.
point - an array with point[0] = x, point[1] = y.

toRect

public static void toRect(double zoom,
                          LatLngRect rect,
                          int[] points)
Converts rect to a rectangle in Mercator pixel space.

Parameters:
zoom - zoom level.
rect - area to convert to a rectangle.
points - an array with at least 4 elements. On return points[offset] = west, points[offset + 1] = south, points[offset + 2] = east, points[offset + 3] = north.

getMetersPerPixel

public static double getMetersPerPixel(double zoom,
                                       LatLng location)
Returns the number of meters per pixel at location.

Important: the screen density is not accounted for by this method, so you may need to multiply the result by the screen density.
